'''225''' ('''two hundred [and] twenty-five''') is the natural number following [[224 (number)|224]] and preceding [[226 (number)|226]]. {{Infobox number | number = 225 | prime = no }}
225 is the smallest number that is a [[polygonal number]] in five different ways.<ref>{{Cite OEIS|A063778|name=a(n) = the least integer that is polygonal in exactly n ways}}</ref> It is a [[square number]] {{nowrap|1=(225 = 15<sup>2</sup>)}},<ref>{{Cite OEIS|A000290|name=The squares}}</ref> an [[octagonal number]],<ref>{{Cite OEIS|A000567|name=Octagonal numbers}}</ref> and a [[squared triangular number]] {{nowrap|1=(225 = (1 + 2 + 3 + 4 + 5)<sup>2</sup> = 1<sup>3</sup> + 2<sup>3</sup> + 3<sup>3</sup> + 4<sup>3</sup> + 5<sup>3</sup>)}} .<ref>{{Cite OEIS|A000537|name=Sum of first n cubes; or n-th triangular number squared}}</ref>
As the square of a [[double factorial]], {{nowrap|1=225 = 5!!<sup>2</sup>}} counts the number of [[permutation]]s of six items in which all cycles have even length, or the number of permutations in which all cycles have odd length.<ref>{{Cite OEIS|A001818|name=Squares of double factorials}}</ref> And as one of the [[Stirling numbers of the first kind]], it counts the number of permutations of six items with exactly three cycles.<ref>{{Cite OEIS|A000399|name=Unsigned Stirling numbers of first kind s(n,3)}}</ref>
225 is a [[Highly composite number|highly composite odd number]], meaning that it has more divisors than any smaller odd numbers.<ref>{{Cite OEIS|A053624|name=Highly composite odd numbers}}</ref> After 1 and 9, 225 is the third smallest number ''n'' for which {{nowrap|1=''&sigma;''(''&phi;''(''n'')) = ''&phi;''(''&sigma;''(''n''))}}, where ''&sigma;'' is the [[Divisor function|sum of divisors function]] and ''&phi;'' is [[Euler's totient function]].<ref>{{Cite OEIS|1=A033632|2=Numbers n such that sigma(phi(n)) = phi(sigma(n))}}</ref> 225 is a [[refactorable number]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://oeis.org/A033950|title=Sloane's A033950 : Refactorable numbers|last=|first=|date=2016-04-18|website=The On-Line Encyclopedia of Integer Sequences|publisher=OEIS Foundation|access-date=2016-04-18}}</ref>
225 is the smallest [[square number]] to have one of every digit in some number base (225 is 3201 in base 4) <ref>{{Cite OEIS|A061845|name=Numbers which have one of every digit in some base}}</ref> ==In other fields== *The years [[225]] and [[225 BC]] *[[.225 Winchester]], firearm cartridge
