==In mathematics== '''230''' is: *a [[composite number]], with its divisors being 2, 5, 10, 23, 46, and 115. *a [[sphenic number]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Sloane's A007304 : Sphenic numbers|url=https://oeis.org/A007304|website=The On-Line Encyclopedia of Integer Sequences|publisher=OEIS Foundation|accessdate=2016-09-05}}</ref> because it is the product of 3 primes. *[[Palindromic number|palindromic]] and a [[repdigit]] in bases 22 (AA<sub>22</sub>), 45 (55<sub>45</sub>), 114 (22<sub>114</sub>), 229 (11<sub>229</sub>) *a [[Harshad number]] in bases 2, 6, 10, 12, 23 (and 16 other bases). *a [[happy number]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sloane's A007770 : Happy numbers|url=https://oeis.org/A007770|website=The On-Line Encyclopedia of Integer Sequences|publisher=OEIS Foundation|accessdate=2016-09-05}}</ref> *a [[nontotient]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Sloane's A005277 : Nontotients|url=https://oeis.org/A005277|website=The On-Line Encyclopedia of Integer Sequences|publisher=OEIS Foundation|accessdate=2016-09-05}}</ref> since there is no integer with 230 [[coprime]]s below it. *the sum of the coprime counts for the first 27 integers. *the [[aliquot sum]] of both [[454 (number)|454]] and 52441. *part of the 41-aliquot tree.
The aliquot sequence starting at 224 is: 224, 280, 440, 640, 890, 730, 602, 454, '''230''', 202, 104, 106, 56, 64, 63, 41, 1, 0.
There are 230 unique [[space group]]s describing all possible crystal symmetries.
==In other fields== 230 is: * A common [[voltage]] in the [[European Union]]. * The year A.D. [[230]] or [[230 BC]]. * +230 is the country code for [[Mauritius]].
